5â€™ scRNA Combined Analysis - Ley

Load libraires

library(Seurat)
library(dplyr)
library(Matrix)

Load the data if saved

#load("5-comb.Robj")

Combine the 5â€™ datasets

aml_55055.data <- Read10X(data.dir = "/mnt/analysis/marsoc/pipestances/H35TMDSXX/SC_RNA_COUNTER_PD/55055/HEAD/outs/filtered_gene_bc_matrices_mex/GRCh38/")
aml_55055 <- CreateSeuratObject(raw.data = aml_55055.data, project = "AML_55055")

aml_55054.data <- Read10X(data.dir = "/mnt/analysis/marsoc/pipestances/H35TMDSXX/SC_RNA_COUNTER_PD/55054/HEAD/outs/filtered_gene_bc_matrices_mex/GRCh38/")
aml_55054 <- CreateSeuratObject(raw.data = aml_55054.data, project = "AML_55054")

#Create the final Seurat object
aml_comb <- MergeSeurat(object1 = aml_55055, object2 = aml_55054, add.cell.id1 = "55055", 
    add.cell.id2 = "55054", project = "5_AML_Comb")

Preprocessing

Visulize gene/gene plots

# GenePlot is typically used to visualize gene-gene relationships, but can
# be used for anything calculated by the object, i.e. columns in
# object@meta.data, PC scores etc.  Since there is a rare subset of cells
# with an outlier level of high mitochondrial percentage and also low UMI
# content, we filter these as well
par(mfrow= c(1,2))
GenePlot(object = pre_aml_comb, gene1 = "nUMI", gene2 = "percent.mito", ylim = c(0,1), pch.use = "o")
GenePlot(object = pre_aml_comb, gene1 = "nUMI", gene2 = "nGene", ylim = c(0, 7000), pch.use = "o")

Filter based on UMI

# We filter out cells that have unique gene counts over 2,500 or less than
# 200 Note that low.thresholds and high.thresholds are used to define a
# 'gate' -Inf and Inf should be used if you don't want a lower or upper
# threshold.
aml_comb <- FilterCells(object = aml_comb, subset.names = c("nGene", "percent.mito"), 
    low.thresholds = c(200, -Inf), high.thresholds = c(2500, 0.05))

Normalize the data

#normalizes the gene expression measurements for each cell by the total expression, multiplies this by a scale factor (10,000 by default), and log-transforms the result.
aml_comb <- NormalizeData(object = aml_comb, normalization.method = "LogNormalize", 
    scale.factor = 10000)

Diffirentiall expressed genes

aml_comb <- FindVariableGenes(object = aml_comb, mean.function = ExpMean, dispersion.function = LogVMR, 
    x.low.cutoff = 0.0125, x.high.cutoff = 3, y.cutoff = 0.5)

Scaling the data and removing unwanted sources of variation

aml_comb <- ScaleData(object = aml_comb, vars.to.regress = c("nUMI", "percent.mito"))

Perform linear dimensional reduction

aml_comb <- RunPCA(object = aml_comb, pc.genes = aml_comb@var.genes, do.print = TRUE, pcs.print = 1:5,

PCA viz

VizPCA(object = aml_comb, pcs.use = 1:2)

PCA plot

PCAPlot(object = aml_comb, dim.1 = 1, dim.2 = 2)

# ProjectPCA scores each gene in the dataset (including genes not included
# in the PCA) based on their correlation with the calculated components.
# Though we don't use this further here, it can be used to identify markers
# that are strongly correlated with cellular heterogeneity, but may not have
# passed through variable gene selection.  The results of the projected PCA
# can be explored by setting use.full=T in the functions above
aml_comb <- ProjectPCA(object = aml_comb, do.print = FALSE)

Heatmaps

PCHeatmap(object = aml_comb, pc.use = 1, cells.use = 500, do.balanced = TRUE, label.columns = FALSE)

Look at more PCs

PCHeatmap(object = aml_comb, pc.use = 1:12, cells.use = 500, do.balanced = TRUE, 
    label.columns = FALSE, use.full = FALSE)

Determine statistically significant principal components

# NOTE: This process can take a long time for big datasets, comment out for
# expediency.  More approximate techniques such as those implemented in
# PCElbowPlot() can be used to reduce computation time
aml_comb <- JackStraw(object = aml_comb, num.replicate = 100, do.print = TRUE)

Plot the PCs

JackStrawPlot(object = aml_comb, PCs = 1:20)

Plot the PCs and pick a cutoff at the elbow

PCElbowPlot(object = aml_comb)

Cluster the cells

# save.SNN = T saves the SNN so that the clustering algorithm can be rerun
# using the same graph but with a different resolution value (see docs for
# full details)
aml_comb <- FindClusters(object = aml_comb, reduction.type = "pca", dims.use = 1:10, 
    resolution = 0.6, print.output = 0, save.SNN = TRUE)

Run Non-linear dimensional reduction (tSNE) and plot

aml_comb <- RunTSNE(object = aml_comb, dims.use = 1:10, do.fast = TRUE)
TSNEPlot(object = aml_comb, do.label = T)

Save the R object

save(aml_comb,mito.genes,percent.mito, file = "5-comb.Robj")

Find distinguising cluster markers

Investigate the clusters

# find all markers of cluster 1
cluster1.markers <- FindMarkers(object = aml_comb, ident.1 = 1, min.pct = 0.25)
print(x = head(x = cluster1.markers, n = 10))

cluster 6 are probably NK cells

# find all markers distinguishing cluster 6 from clusters 0-5
cluster6.markers <- FindMarkers(object = aml_comb, ident.1 = 6, ident.2 = c(0:5), 
    min.pct = 0.25)
print(x = head(x = cluster6.markers, n = 10))

Cluster 7 are probably B-cells

# find all markers distinguishing cluster 7 from clusters 0-5
cluster7.markers <- FindMarkers(object = aml_comb, ident.1 = 7, ident.2 = c(0:5), 
    min.pct = 0.25)
print(x = head(x = cluster7.markers, n = 10))

cluster 8 probably cytotoxic T lymphocytes or natural killer cells

# find all markers distinguishing cluster 8 from clusters 0-5
cluster8.markers <- FindMarkers(object = aml_comb, ident.1 = 8, ident.2 = c(0:5), 
    min.pct = 0.25)
print(x = head(x = cluster8.markers, n = 10))

Find markers for all clusters

Test clasification based on ROC

cluster1.markers <- FindMarkers(object = aml_comb, ident.1 = 0, thresh.use = 0.25, 
    test.use = "roc", only.pos = TRUE)
